    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Tiny, parallel-sided isopod with reduced eyes and rectangular thoracic segments, the sides of the last few being bent backwards. Abdomen of one short free segment, remaining segments fused with telson to form a ‘pleotelson’. Pleotelson rounded. Body covered in fine pile of tiny hairs. Best identified by its unusual habitat within the brood pouches of larger isopods.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_451",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 2.5 mm, excluding antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_452",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread in Southern Hemisphere, including South America, South Africa, New Zealand, Tasmania and various subantarctic islands.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Lüderitz in Namibia to KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_453",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>May be found free-living, but usually recorded from within the brood pouches of larger sphaeromid isopods, such as <i>Exosphaeroma, Parisocladus, Sphaeroma, Dymanenella</i> and <i>Sphaeromene</i>. Up to 25 commensals may be found within the brood pouch of a single host, but these do not appear to detract from the development of host eggs.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_454",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Not known, but do not appear to damage the eggs of the host.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_455",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>As with all isopods the eggs are retained in a brood pouch beneath the walking legs of females. Due to the small adult size, egg numbers are unusually low, with a maximum of only 14 eggs produced per female. Breeding is thought to be continuous throughout the year and lifespan is only about 7 months.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_456",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The unusual habitat and pubescent texture of the body mean that this species is unlikely to be confused with any other.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_457",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Kensley, B (1978). Guide to the Marine Isodods of Southern Africa. <i>Trustees of the South African Museum</i>, Cape Town. 173 pp. (p. 135).<br><br>Marsden, ID (1982). Population biology of the commensal asellotan <i>Iais pubescens</i> (Dana) and its sphaeromatid host <i>Exosphaeroma obtusum</i> (Dana)(Isopoda). <i>Journal of Experimental Marine Biology and Ecology</i>, 58(2–3), 233–257.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_458",
